<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Nato offers warplanes to defend UN troops in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATO is to offer warplanes to defend United Nations troops in Bosnia,
although the allies appeared yesterday to disagree over the circumstances in
which they would be deployed.
Croatian gunmen, meanwhile, held up a relief convoy taking supplies to
Moslems in Bosnia and shot dead at least eight civilian drivers. The gunmen
then looted the lorries before UN peacekeeping troops could intervene.
The Nato offer of warplanes came in response to a suggestion by Mr Boutros
Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general, that Nato should be given the task
of providing such protective air power on the UN's behalf. It was made
public at the beginning of a two-day Nato foreign ministers' meeting in
Athens.
It was also announced that a Nato summit, proposed by US president Bill
Clinton, would be held in December to give member countries an opportunity
to adapt the alliance's agenda to the post-cold war world.
Significantly, the communique issued after yesterday's Nato meeting does not
restrict air protection in Bosnia to the six Moslem enclaves within the
republic. 'We offer our protective air power in case of attack against
Unprofor (UN Protection Forces) in the performance of its overall mandate,'
the document stated.
Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, indicated that this meant air
power could be used to protect UN forces anywhere in Bosnia, if called on to
do so. What it did not mean was that air strikes would be used to protect
the civilian population from attack.
This interpretation was supported by Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign
secretary, though Mr Alain Juppe, French foreign minister, was of the view
that air power would be used only to protect Unprofor troops in the
officially designated safe areas.
The need to work out a common position on former Yugoslavia, together with
the closely related issue of co-operation on world peacekeeping operations,
is likely to figure prominently at the Nato summit, to be held at a venue in
Europe to be decided.
Mr Christopher also announced that the US had offered to contribute 300
troops to the UN peacekeeping contingent in the former Yugoslav republic of
Macedonia. This now numbers about 700 and is intended to prevent the
Yugoslav conflict spilling over into Macedonia.
'This offer of US troops to the UN has both symbolic and tangible
significance. These troops underscore the seriousness of our warning to
Belgrade and the Bosnian Serbs,' Mr Christopher told the Nato council.
He stressed at a news conference, however, that Washington would not provide
ground troops for the protection of Moslem 'safe areas' in Bosnia.
The relief convoy attacked in Bosnia was heading for the mainly Moslem town
of Tuzla, when it was halted near the disputed town of Novi Travnik. UN
officials said Croat gunmen ransacked some of the 170 lorries.
'I saw drivers being dragged from their vehicles,' said a British corporal
attached to the UN peacekeeping troops trying to protect the convoy. 'I then
heard a series of shots and a little later I saw a number of bodies being
dragged away.'
Fragile ceasefire, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
