<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: E German perlite plan targets
builders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OTAVI MINEN, a subsidiary of the British-based Cookson Group, will double
its production of perlite in eastern Germany in a move aimed at targeting
the expanding construction industry.
The company, the third largest in Europe, recently invested DM9.8m (Pounds
4m) in building a modern perlite insulation plant at Buelstringen, near
Magdeburg. Perlite, which is extracted from the perlite surface mines on the
Greek island of Milos, is used for insulation material between walls of
houses and offices and in roof coverings.
The decision to locate in eastern Germany stems partly from the steady
expansion in the construction sector, as well as transportation costs -
perlite is a very light commodity. By locating the plant in the middle of
its market, Cookson intends to gain a sizeable foothold in eastern Germany,
as well as complement its western German operations.
The Buelstringen is already producing 30,000 tonnes a year with a staff of
14. Cookson expects to double its staff and boost output by 80,000 tonnes to
120,000 tonnes by 1994.
