<DATE>930611
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / International Company News: Salomon to pay Dollars 54.5m to
settle lawsuits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SALOMON Brothers, the Wall Street securities house, announced yesterday that
it had agreed to pay Dollars 54.5m to settle class action lawsuits filed by
the firm's shareholders and debtholders in the wake of the 1991 bond auction
scandal.
The scandal, which nearly destroyed one of Wall Street's most powerful
firms, erupted when Salomon's bond trading desk was discovered to have faked
customer bids for Treasury securities in a number of bond auctions during
1990 and 1991.
The false bids were part of an attempt by Salomon's chief bond trader to
avoid government rules limiting how many bonds securities firms were allowed
to acquire in each auction.
Yesterday's settlement, however, will not involve Salomon paying any new
money, as the Dollars 54.5m will come out of the Dollars 100m fund the firm
set up in May 1992 to compensate victims of its violations. The fund was
established as part of the settlement reached with the government last year.
At the time, Salomon also paid Dollars 190m in fines and forfeitures for its
actions.
Additionally, Salomon said yesterday that it had agreed to pay all legal
fees incurred in the shareholder and debtholders' action, up to a maximum of
Dollars 12.5m. That money will not come out of the Dollars 100m compensation
fund, but will be paid directly by the firm.
Although this latest settlement is an important step for Salomon, it does
not represent the final chapter in the bond auction scandal. The firm still
has to fight litigation brought by investors who purchased government
securities in 1990 and 1991 and who claim they suffered losses.
The firm is expected to fight these actions more vigorously than it did the
lawsuits settled yesterday. Senior Salomon executives knew of the illegal
activities for months before they were publicly revealed, so the firm had
little choice but to reach a settlement.
Also, Mr Paul Mozer, the former head bond trader at Salomon who allegedly
faked the customer bids in Treasury auctions, still faces trial for his
actions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
