<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Staveley rises 9% despite fall in margins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STAVELEY, the measuring and mechanical engineering company which also owns
British Salt, reported a 9 per cent increase in pre-tax profits last year
but a deterioration in trading and operating margins.
The mechanical and electrical services division suffered from depressed
conditions in the construction industry. But measurement, which makes
weighing machinery, and minerals, which produces more than half the UK's
salt, both increased profits.
Pre-tax profits rose from Pounds 22.4m to Pounds 24.4m on sales up 15.6 per
cent at Pounds 344.9m. Underlying organic sales growth was 10 per cent - the
balance arising from an acquisition and the effect of translating foreign
currency sales.
Earnings per share rose from 15.1p to 16.1p and the group is to pay a final
dividend of 6.2p, giving 8.5p in total, up 3.7 per cent.
Measurement produced operating profits of Pounds 8.4m (Pounds 8.1m) from
sales of Pounds 153m. Mr Brian Kent, chairman, said margins should be double
this year. Growth in this division would come from the introduction of new
products.
Profits from mechanical and electrical services fell to Pounds 4.4m (Pounds
5.6m) on sales up 18 per cent at Pounds 152.9m. Mr Kent said the fall in the
construction industry had bottomed out and there was recovery potential from
a stronger order book.
Minerals produced operating profits of Pounds 12.2m (Pounds 11.8m) on sales
of Pounds 32.9m despite price controls.
Gearing rose from 11 per cent to 22 per cent with net debt up from Pounds
11m to Pounds 20m, partly as a result of translating dollar denominated debt
after sterling left the ERM. Capital expenditure was lifted by a Pounds 4m
investment in plant to help expand sales of salt products.
</TEXT>
