<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Difficult markets leave Watson &amp; Philip
lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIFFICULT markets in retail services and cash and carry pushed interim
pre-tax profits at Watson &amp; Philip, the food wholesaler and retailer, down
from Pounds 4.14m to Pounds 4.01m after interest costs of Pounds 306,000,
against income of Pounds 28,000.
Turnover in the 26 weeks to April 30, helped by 10 weeks contribution from
Circle K, the Pounds 21m convenience store chain acquisition, improved to
Pounds 265.1m, against Pounds 240.4m in the 27 weeks to May 1 1992.
Trading profits were Pounds 4.7m (Pounds 4.31m) helped by Pounds 684,000
from Circle K and increases in the Foodservice side.
Mr Ian MacPherson, chairman, said retail services and sales to shops the
company did not own, continued to decline, particularly in the southern half
of England. 'This confirms our belief that the strategy of expanding our
wholly owned network is essential.'
He said the main reason for the fall in cash and carry profits was 'a
substantial decline in trading margins from 1.69 per cent to 1.11 per cent',
because of increased competition in a 'static to declining market'.
The interest charge this time reflected the acquisition and increased
working capital at Foodservice. Period end debt of Pounds 13m gave gearing
of about 25 per cent.
The board declared a 4.4p (4.2p) interim dividend although earnings declined
to 8.1p (8.2p).
