<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Pilkington cuts dividend for the second time: Profits more
than halved as German market collapses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PILKINGTON yesterday cut its annual dividend by a third to 4p, despite
having held the interim payment in December.
The share price fell 6p to 130p.
Last summer the glass group, whose profits have slumped during the
recession, cut its dividend for the first time since it went public in 1970.
Pilkington, which makes two interim payments, last year reduced the second
interim from 7.57p to 3.07p. This time it has been cut to 1.07p. The first
interim has been held at 2.93p.
Annual pre-tax profits for the year to March fell from Pounds 95.7m to
Pounds 40.7m on sales of Pounds 2.57bn, against Pounds 2.61bn.
The dividend cut saves the company Pounds 16m plus associated tax payments.
Even so, the high tax charge of Pounds 46m, up from Pounds 43.8m, and the
remaining dividend bill caused a retained loss of Pounds 51.4m, compared
with a deficit of Pounds 20.1m. The loss per share was 2.6p against earnings
of 3.5p.
In December the company justified holding the dividend by saying it was
'marginally more optimistic'. Sir Antony Pilkington, chairman, said
yesterday that most of the encouraging trends the group had seen in December
had continued, but there had also been 'a dramatic collapse' in Germany,
where the situation remained uncertain. Pilkington's German business
contributed a third of group operating profits.
In January, the German carmakers which Pilkington supplies, such as Mercedes
and BMW, 'virtually shut down for four weeks,' said Mr Roger Leverton, chief
executive. Sales of glass to the housebuilding industry had held up but
prices were under pressure.
Analysts speculated that the dividend cut showed Mr Leverton, who joined the
group in July last year, had had more of a say in the decision. Sir Antony
is thought to have wanted to maintain the payout.
Sir Antony said that improving signs included a pick up in profits in the
group's southern hemisphere operations, and the 'amazing difference' that
sterling's devaluation had made to the UK operations' competitiveness. In
the second half of the financial year float glass volumes were the highest
they had been for three years. Costs savings had been achieved and an 8 per
cent price rise in the UK was sticking.
Although group borrowings had risen from Pounds 760m to Pounds 932m, Sir
Antony said there was no need for a rights issue as disposals would cut
debt.
He added that an investigation was progressing at Libbey-Owens-Ford -
Pilkington's North American subsidiary where three top executives, including
the president, have been suspended after apparent breaches of company
procedures. Legal proceedings against a third party had been instituted. The
business was continuing normally.
Lex Page 14; Details, Page 19; London SE, Page 34
</TEXT>
