FT  11 JUN 93 / Letter: Unexpected vintage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From REINIE BOOYSEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Of course, I would never want to be accused of placing facts in the way
of a good story, but Observer ('Loosening up', June 8) has translated an
Afrikaans/Dutch word incorrectly. Actually, the anecdote is even better with
the correct translation.
Buitenverwachting - the wine served by the ANC newspaper, New Nation, when
Roelf Meyer, the government negotiator, and ANC secretary-general Cyril
Ramaphosa jointly accepted the 'man of the year award' - actually means
'beyond expectations', and not 'waiting outside'. In contrast with
Allesverloren (all is lost), the wine served to Meyer shortly after
President De Klerk's 1990 speech un-banning the ANC, it would seem the talks
are going better than some fear.
Reinie Booysen,
