<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The schedules are packed with repeats, and Fridays are no longer saved by
'Have I Got News For You' which ended its run last week with a tub of lard
standing in for Roy Hattersley who, we were told, had failed to turn up for
the third time. Thus it is an excellent day for taking advantage of the long
evenings and getting to work in the garden. You could wear a Walkman and
listen to The Movie Quiz on Radio 2 (7.00) ..stick the mobile phone in your
pocket and you could even take part and win yourself a year's cinema pass
for two. Switch to Radio 3 at 7.30 and you can listen to the BBC
Philharmonic In Cambridge playing music by four contemporary Cambridge
composers: Alexander Goehr, Hugh Wood, Thomas Ades (who graduated from
King's last year with a double starred first) and Robin Holloway. Flick over
to Radio 4 when that ends and you will catch the final part of John
Diamond's programme about the week's newspapers, Stop Press and then a
repeat of Kaleidoscope's award-winning programme 'Larks Ascending' about
Vaughan Williams' evocation of the British countryside (9.15).
</TEXT>
