<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Accountancy income dented: Competition and recession dent
earnings, league table shows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Intense competition and the effects of the recession severly dented the
income of the UK's acountancy firms during the last year, according to the
Fincial Times laegue table of the profession published today.
Fee income excluding expenses for the largest 30 firms was almost unchanged
between 1991-92 and 1992-93, while the number of partners professional staff
and offices fell sunstantially.
Two-thirds of the firms reported an absolute decline in income and most of
the increases were in single digits. The greatest growth was 17.5 per cent
at Andersen - comprising Arthur Andersen and Andersen Consulting - and the
largest decline was 11.1 per cent at Casson Beckman.
Overall fee income rose just 0.2 per cent to $3.4bn, indicating stagnation
in the sector but also demonstrating the tremendous revenues now generated
by the profession.
The figures also show the growing dominance of the 'Big 6' firms, which
alone generated revenues of $2.6bn during the past year - or three quarters
of the total.
A year ago Coopers &amp; Lybrand was the only Big 6 firm to report a decline in
fee income. This year only one of the Big 6 - Andersen - has managed to
report any growth.
Across the firms (excluding Reeves &amp; Neylan, for which there were no
comparative figures) the number of partners fell by 4 per cent to 5,010.
Other professional staff fell nearly 6 per cent to 43,449.
The results show the growing diversity of services provided by accountants.
Among those which break out activities, audit and related accounting
services compromises on average just 41 per cent of total fee income. It is
below half for all but 11 of the 30 firms. Total audit fees fell 2.4 per
cent to $1.4bn during the period.
Insolvency income - now making up 11 per cnet of the total - rose by 10.8
per cent to $389m. It accounts for as much as 43 per cent of income for Levy
Gee and 27 per cent at Robson Rhodes.
Tax recenues - 23 per cent of the total - dropped 0.3 per cent to $787m,
while those from consulting - 20 per cent of the total - rose 1 per cent to
$674m.
Beyond the four prinicipal divisions there are many other activities, such
as $1.9m generated by the corporate finance group at KPMG Peat Marwick.
Acountancy firms ar under no legal obligation to publish financial
information because they are private partnerships. They persistently refuse
to provide details of profits. Andersen has the highest ratio of
professional staff to partners and the highest fees generated by each
partner, at nearly $1.6m.
The figures are adjusted as far as posible to allow for comparisons, but
many of the stated year-ends are different, and other factors such as
mergers and widely differing structures confuse the position.
Several - such as Moore Rowlands - are associations of different firms
rather than a unified organsiation, while a number of others - like BDO
Binder Hamlyn and KPMG Peat Marwick - compromise separate partnerships.
</TEXT>
