<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Chemical cargo caution by DoT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MILNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHEMICAL cargoes may be inadequately insured against disaster, a senior
civil servant warned yesterday.
Department of Transport official Mr Frank Wall was giving evidence to the
Donaldson inquiry into the Braer oil disaster off Shetland.
The maximum liability is between Pounds 2.3m and Pounds 30m compared with
Pounds 129m available after a serious oil spill.
Mr Wall said the government was frustrated by the lack of progress towards
an international agreement in spite of 20 years of diplomatic wrangling.
He warned that the world seemed to be waiting for the chemical equivalent of
an accident like the Titanic or the Amoco Cadiz before acting.
A draft convention is being considered by the International Maritime
Organisation but it is hampered by the definition of hazardous cargo and
whetherthat should cover material in bulk or in packages.
The London hearing was told that 400 claims were lodged after the Braer
spill, and 244 had been settled by the International Oil Pollution
Compensation Fund. Slightly more than Pounds 10m had been paid out.
</TEXT>
