<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Company car drivers shun cash
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FEWER than one in 20 company car drivers say they will give up their cars in
exchange for cash from their employers before a tax system is introduced
next April, although most drivers expect to pay more under the new regime, a
Mori survey shows.
Publication of the survey, carried out for Lex Service group's vehicle
leasing subsidiary, follows hard on the heels of a report from employee
benefits specialists Stoy Benefit Consulting. This concluded that nearly six
out of 10 UK executives would be better off by handing back their company
cars in exchange for extra pay and a mileage allowance to run their own
cars.
The Mori survey of more than 600 company car drivers found that 72 per cent
expected to pay more tax, but 52 per cent said the new regime would have no
effect on either the type of car they drove or its specification.
Lex Report on Motoring, Lex Vehicle Leasing, Globe House, Parkway, Globe
Park, Marlow, Bucks SL7 1LY. Pounds 95.
</TEXT>
