<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Imro backs down over training proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMRO, the self-regulating body for the fund management industry, has
withdrawn controversial proposals for the training of professionals that
would require fund managers to undergo 50 hours of continuing education each
year.
The proposals, released in April, sparked protests from Imro members who
claimed the rules were arbitrary, unnecessary and unenforceable. The
Institutional Fund Managers Association, an industry trade body, had earlier
met both Imro and the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief
regulatory watchdog, to register its objections.
The drafting of the training rules followed an SIB directive to all four of
the City's self-regulating bodies that they set training and competence
requirements for employees of their member companies. An earlier set of
proposals for training and competence rules for Imro members had been
criticised by the SIB for falling short of the regimen set out by the other
self-regulating bodies.
In a letter to Imro members earlier this week, chief executive Mr John
Morgan noted the industry concerns and said Imro had decided to review the
proposals. Instead, the organisation will prepare a new consultation
document, to be released in July, which will take into account all the
objections raised by its members 'to ensure that full weight is given to all
concerns', he said.
</TEXT>
