<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Sotheby's helps to bail out Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOTHEBY'S, the London auction house, is offering a discreet tailor-made
service to Lloyd's Names who want to sell the family silver - or other
heirlooms.
'We are not coffin chasers, but we have a market where a lot of people are
looking to raise capital,' said Mr James Miller of Sotheby's.
It has received 'thousands' of inquiries in recent months from Names,
individuals whose capital underwrites the insurance market. Sotheby's is to
meet members' agents next week to advise on auction rescue packages.
The meeting, the first of its kind in Lloyd's 300-year-old history, comes as
many Names are close to ruin.
The auction house offers Names a 40 per cent discount on commission, loans
of up to 35 per cent on the value of objects sent for sale and free surveys.
It also promises 'total anonymity'.
Mr Miller heads a special advisory service which is already dealing with
about 2,000 Names, most of whom are seeking to raise between Pounds 50,000
and Pounds 100,000.
Sotheby's counsels them about which objects to sell: 'Some people might say
'I can't bear to sell that painting - what about the candlesticks?' But we
might have to point out that there are already lots of candlesticks on the
market, so why don't they look at the chest of drawers?'
The main objects being sold are silver, jewellery, paintings and furniture.
Sotheby's said the flood of new pieces had not, as yet, triggered a
significant fall in their prices for silver and jewellery, although prices
in the furniture market have dipped in the last year.
'Most of the silver does seem to be mopped up,' said Mr Richard Came, silver
consultant at Sotheby's.
Among the hard hit Names themselves, the mood is more bitter. 'It's a
buyers' market', said Mr Norbet Mallet, who, as a result of losses of more
than Pounds 1m with the Gooda Walker syndicates, has had to sell most of his
family jewellery in the last two years, at prices he believes are 'some 30
per cent lower' than 1980s prices.
