<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Lloyd's tightens rules on EGMs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF London yesterday amended rules under which its Names can call
extraordinary general meetings. The move came amid fears that such
gatherings could undermine the confidence of potential investors at the
insurance market.
The decision increases the minimum number of signatures of Names - the
individuals whose assets support the market - needed for a meeting to be
called from 100 to 1,500. It is not retrospective, however and does not
affect the EGM called by supporters of Mr Claud Gurney and arranged for July
5.
Mr David Rowland, chairman, said: 'I am very concerned with the disruption.
I must do everything I can to maintain confidence.'
The changes had been introduced 'to bring Lloyd's more into line with
company procedures giving members of Lloyd's rights similar to shareholders
in companies'.
An EGM organised last year had cost more than Pounds 130,000, and had
disrupted the business of the market.
Mr Rowland added: 'I can't begin to explain the enormous diversion of
management time. If we are going to take the society through to a better
future we have to be free to run it.'
The decision met a mixed response from Names. Mr Neil Shaw, chairman of the
Association of Lloyd's Members, the biggest Names' organisation, said that
the change 'must not muzzle criticism or blunt reform of Lloyd's in any
way'.
He said, however, that the council 'has made a commonsense response in
changing this unrealistic byelaw, and we believe the membership will
benefit'.
Mr Richard Astor, a lawyer campaigning on behalf of Names, said that the
change would not thwart his own efforts to hold an EGM calling for the
liquidation of Lloyd's. 'Lloyd's can run but not hide,' he said. 'This
pathetic attempt to compare itself with company procedures will rebound.'
Mr Astor also disclosed yesterday that he was organising legal action
against at least two former chairmen of the insurance market.
He would not reveal the identity of the former chairmen concerned but said
Names intended to issue procedings alleging deceit soon.
'The chairmen owed fiduciary duties which they breached. They obtained the
deposits of Lloyd's Names by deception,' Mr Astor said.
</TEXT>
