<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Major's Leadership in Crisis: Soldiers await firm orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMONG THE battle-scarred foot soldiers in the Tory ranks at Westminster the
widespread message for Mr John Major is that they would like the prime
minister to tell them more clearly and more often where they are going - and
why they are fighting.
As for the charges levelled by Mr Norman Lamont, many backbenchers agreed
that there was too much short-termism - 'bouncing along from crisis to
crisis' - as one put it, but other MPs commented ruefully that they would
have welcomed signs of ministers paying closer attention to opinion
pollsters.
Tories across the party accept that concessions in response to potential
Commons rebellions and changes to unpopular policies are a necessary part of
governing with a small majority when people generally still do not feel
confident about the economy.
But there are doubts - most forcefully expressed on the right of the party -
about how thoroughly changes are made, and anxiety that sometimes the least
objectionable rather than the right solution is found. 'You can trim a bit
too far,' said one MP.
Backbenchers with little sympathy for Mr Lamont's argument were quick to
accuse him of sour grapes, and to suggest that the populist decision that he
had primarily in mind was his own dismissal.
As for any broader point: 'If he felt like that, why didn't he speak out
while he was still in cabinet?' one loyalist asked.
MPs seeking to rebut the charge that policies were taken for short-term
popularity rather than for the long term, at times seemed spoiled for
choice. Rail privatisation, education reform and measures to restore the
state of public finances - including the imposition of value added tax on
domestic fuel - were all cited.
Above all, there was the issue that has riven the Tory party for more than a
year. One MP said with feeling: 'You can't really accuse a government which
put us all through the torture of Maastricht of having its eyes on
short-term popularity.'
Even those who do not accept Mr Lamont's account of the working of
government, believe that there are ways in which Mr Major should improve his
performance. One former minister advised him to ignore the newspapers, while
several said he should find himself some new advisers and aides.
The most serious concern was that the prime minister did not use the
opportunity of Wednesday's speech to spell out where the Tory party was
heading and did not offer his Commons troops a way forward which they could
cheer.
A junior minister said: 'He needed to set out a context, a vision. When you
talk to him one-to-one you get a clear idea of where he's coming from, but
that gets lost when he speaks in the Commons.'
Another put it more bluntly: 'He should be more prime ministerial.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9111 Executive Offices.
</IN>
