<PROFILE>_AN-DFKB5AB2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930611
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Fowler in passionate attack against
Lamont
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PERSONAL attack by Sir Norman Fowler, Tory chairman, on Mr Norman Lamont
yesterday was passionate, finger-jabbing - and encouraged fears among Tory
MPs that much of the party hierarchy is in a nervous panic.
Sir Norman made no attempt to rise above the Westminster fray caused by the
former chancellor's speech, or try to appeal for calm. It was 'frankly
ludicrous,' he said.
Rarely, if ever, have such vitriolic comments been made by one senior
Conservative about another and it was noticeble that Sir Norman was not
joined in his abuse by cabinet members. The prime minister's office said
merely that Sir Norman was expressing his 'personal view'.
One rightwing MP sympathetic to the plight of Mr Lamont said the party
chairman's outburst had been 'appalling'. At the backbench 1922 committee
meeting last night Sir Norman faced further criticism.
Some Tory MPs said the best tactic would have been to be statesmanlike,
refusing to be provoked but merely expressing regret and rebutting calming
Mr Lamont's points.
That was more the approach of Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, and Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary. 'If you sack your
chancellor, you know there will be a price to pay,' said Mr Heseltine. 'It
always was that way; it always will be.'
Mr Howard said the former chancellor's intervention would prove a nine-day
wonder. 'I very much regret that Norman Lamont made the speech,' he added.
The consensus view among Conservative MPs remained that Mr Lamont had less
political weight that Sir Geoffrey Howe, whose resignation speech
precipitated Baroness Thatcher's downfall.
But Sir Norman said Mr Lamont was a man 'thrashing around for culprits for
his own position'. Speaking on GMTV, Sir Norman repeatedly jabbed his finger
at the camera, his face flushing pink. 'It was a dud speech,' he said. 'It
was a nasty speech. And I do not think many people are going to take much
notice of Mr Lamont.'
He said it was 'silly' of Mr Lamont to have suggested in his resignation
speech that the government was living 36 hours at a time.
</TEXT>
