<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Battle is rejoined over health
service funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN's health managers yesterday reopened the question of how the
National Health Service should be financed with a set of radical ideas that
coincide with the timing of the government's public spending review.
For the first time, the Institute of Health Services Management has
qualified its strong support for retaining the tax-based system of funding
the NHS, saying that 'the limitations of general taxation are increasingly
evident'. Mr David Knowles, the institute's president, told its annual
conference in Birmingham that unelected health authorities lacked 'an
adequate level of legitimacy'. He suggested some health responsibilities
could be transferred to local authorities.
An institute working party examining the future of the NHS, following the
government's 1991 reforms, concluded in a report published yesterday that
funding by general taxation alone placed the service at the mercy of
Whitehall. The institute suggested the possibility of supplementing tax
funding through social insurance, financed by a payroll tax, a dedicated
income tax or local taxation.
The Thatcher government considered many such alternatives in a review
leading to the reforms, but rejected them. Health ministers have no desire
for the public spending review now being undertaken by Mr Michael Portillo,
chief secretary at the Treasury, to reopen the funding issue - but
continuing spending pressures could do so.
The Department of Health is also conducting a review of NHS structure, which
is due to report next month.
Mr Knowles told the conference that local decisions on health spending
priorities could be achieved only through local democracy.
Before the 1991 reforms health authorities, meeting in public and with some
members nominated by local authorities, looked recognisably like public
bodies.
'Their replacement, however, with smaller, much more managerially focused,
bodies has shifted the balance of their accountability and legitimacy,' Mr
Knowles said.
The Conservative-dominated Commons' health select committee yesterday
recommended that free dental check-ups and routine treatment should be
available to everyone.
This would mean an end to the present charges for services such as check-ups
and X-rays.
The cross-party committee of MPs said patients would have to pay for other
dental work, such as crowns and bridgework, up to a maximum of Pounds 250 as
currently.
People who are exempt from these services would continue to receive them
free of charge, they added.
</TEXT>
