<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Consumers 'sceptical of decisions
by ombudsmen'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HALF the consumers questioned for a report on ombudsmen thought the
decisions they took were unfair, the National Consumer Council said
yesterday.
A third of those asked questioned the independence of the Office of Building
Societies Ombudsmen Scheme and the Insurance Ombudsmen Bureau, the council
said.
The council also reported 'widespread dissatisfaction' with the time taken
to settle disputes.
The average time taken for disputes to be settled was 52 weeks in the case
of the insurance ombudsman and 91 weeks for the building societies
ombudsman.
However, Dr Julian Farrand, the insurance ombudsman, and Mr Stephen Edell,
one of two building societies ombudsmen, protested at the strength of the
council's comments.
Lady Wilcox, who chairs the consumer council, said: 'Our report shows
clearly that ombudsmen provide a cheap and accessible way to resolve
disputes. However, the extent of dissatisfaction revealed in our survey does
show considerable room for improvement.'
The report, based on a sample of just under 1,000 consumers who had used the
ombudsmen schemes, found that 43 per cent of those using the building
society Ombudsman's scheme found it took an 'unreasonably long time to make
a decision'.
Consumers' views about fairness depended largely on whether they had won
their case.
Ombudsmen Services: Consumers' Views of the Office of the Building Societies
Ombudsmen and the Insurance Ombudsman Bureau, National Consumer Council, 20
Grosvenor Gardens, London SW1W 0DH, Pounds 7.
</TEXT>
