<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: DTI merger plan for research labs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW National Centre for Environmental Technology is to be formed following
a controversial merger announced by the government yesterday between AEA
Technology and the Warren Spring Labor-atory.
The announcement by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
means that Warren Spring - the country's leading applied environmental
research laboratory, based near Stevenage, Herts - will close. As many as
possible of the 200 scientists will be transferred to AEA Technology's
laboratories at Harwell and Culham in Oxfordshire.
Mr Heseltine said in a Commons written answer that uniting Britain's two
main bases of environmental research would create a single centre of
excellence, but there was strong criticism of the proposal from the Warren
Spring workforce and from the Opposition.
Mr Chris Smith, shadow environment spokesman, said the closure was a
disaster for the environment. 'The decision will destroy Warren Spring's
independent identity and remove at a stroke a substantial part of its
expertise . . it is clear the exercise is being undertaken purely as a
fattening up preparation for privatisation,' he said.
Mr Joe Magee of the Institution of Professional Managers and Specialists
said the announcement betrayed the government's obligations to the
environment and industry, and broke a pledge to await the outcome of the
review of all five DTI research laboratories.
But Mr Heseltine said the merger would provide a more comprehensive service
and give better value for money.
