<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Press and privacy white paper
'soon'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A WHITE paper setting out the government's views on press self-regulation
and invasion of privacy by the media will be published before the end of
next month, Mr Peter Brooke, heritage secretary, announced last night.
He also said that the government remained reluctant to accept the
recommendation by Sir David Calcutt that a statutory press complaints
tri-bunal should be established.
Mr Brooke promised to take into account the strength of support among MPs
for the appointment of a press ombudsman reflected in a debate on a report
by the Commons heritage committee on privacy and media intrusion.
The committee suggested that the ombudsman should be able to adjudicate on
complaints about decisions reached by a new voluntary press commission able
to require newspapers to correct in-accuracies and impose fines.
Newspapers and complainants would be able to appeal to the High Court to
overturn decisions made by the ombudsman.
Mr Gerald Kaufman (Lab Manchester Gorton), chairman of the cross-party
committee, envisaged the ombudsman having a 'back-up' role which provided a
stimulus for voluntary regulation.
He welcomed moves already made by the existing Press Complaints Commission
to give effect to some of the recommendations made by the committee.
Ms Ann Clwyd, the shadow heritage secretary, said a future Labour government
would order an inquiry by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission into the
ownership of the press.
She said: 'When Mr Rupert Murdoch can own 35 per cent of weekday newspaper
circulation that, in the eyes of most people, is a quite unacceptable
concentration of power.'
