<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Letter 'targets' invalidity benefit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVALIDITY benefits could become an early casualty of the government's
spending review, according to a confidential government letter leaked
yesterday.
The letter, apparently written to the prime minister from Mr Peter Lilley,
Social Security Secretary, and Mr Michael Portillo, the two government
ministers spearheading the spending review, proposes a controversial 'three
pronged' course of action to cut invalidity benefits.
This would make invalidity benefit less generous, limited to a smaller group
of long-term sick, and taxable.
Noting that 'these changes are bound to be controversial', the letter
suggests that the climate of opinion has now shifted sufficiently to allow
the measures to gain parliamentary support.
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow Social Security Secretary, yesterday condemned the
letter, and called on Mr Lilley to 'kill a proposal which is totally
unacceptable' at the earliest opportunity.
According to the letter, the proposed cuts would save Pounds 180m in the
1995-6 financial year, Pounds 495m in the following year, and Pounds 1.3bn
by the end of the decade.
The bulk of this saving would be made through the introduction of stricter
medical controls on claimants, which the letter suggests would save Pounds
240m over the next three years.
Savings could also be made, the letter suggests, by phasing out the payment
of additional pension, on top of invalidity benefits.
The letter says cuts are necessary because of a 'dramatic growth in
invalidity benefit', as the number of claimants between 1978 and the present
has risen from 600,000 to 1.5m, and total expenditure grown from Pounds 840m
to Pounds 6.2bn, with a projected rise to Pounds 8.2bn in 1995.
</TEXT>
