<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour pledge on press ownership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FUTURE Labour govern-ment would order an inquiry by the Monopolies and
Mergers commission into the ownership of the press, Ms Ann Clwyd, shadow
heritage secretary, told the Commons last night.
She said: 'When Mr Rupert Murdoch can own 35 per cent of weekday newspaper
circulation that, in the eyes of most people, is a quite unacceptable
concentration of power.'
Ms Clwyd also complained that Mr Murdoch's acolytes were now arguing that he
should be allowed to take over large tracts of British television.
She said a Labour government would look at ways of bringing more diversity
to local, regional and national newspapers.
During a debate on the Commons heritage committee report on media intrusion,
Ms Clwyd joined MPs from both sides of the House in opposing statutory
regulation of the press.
Mr Gerald Kaufman (Lab Manchester Gorton), chairman of the committee, and Mr
Paul Channon, the former Conservative cabinet minister, were among leading
members of the committee who urged the government to appoint an ombudsman to
deal with complaints not satisfactorily resolved by a voluntary press
commission.
Mr Kaufman envisaged the ombudsman having a 'back-up' role which provided a
stimulus for voluntary regulation.
He welcomed moves already made by the existing Press Complaints Commission
to give effect to some of the recommendations made by the heritage
committee.
</TEXT>
