<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Convoy ambush sparks fresh Bosnia fighting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ATTACK on a relief convoy in Bosnia led to a fresh upsurge of fighting
between Moslems and Croats yesterday. At the same time clashes between
Moslems and Bosnian Serbs also escalated on several fronts, Reuter reports.
Croatian gunmen pounced on a column of some 170 trucks taking food and other
supplies to the Moslem town of Tuzla. United Nations sources said at least
eight civilian drivers were dragged from their cabins and shot. Croats then
ransacked and looted some of the trucks.
The attack, near the disputed town of Novi Travnik, prompted a fresh
outburst of fighting in the area. Flashes from exploding artillery shells
were seen to the south-east of Novi Travnik as Moslem artillery evidently
resumed blasting Croatian targets.
Croat-Moslem battles over the past few days have killed hundreds and driven
thousands of Croats from their homes in the region.
Fighting between Moslems and Serbs, meanwhile, appeared to be intensifying
on several fronts.
The Bosnian capital of Sarajevo shook to the noise of mortar and artillery
shells after darkness fell. Hospital and mortuary officials reported that at
least six people had been killed and 37 wounded in the latest barrage.
Sarajevo radio said 3,000 shells had crashed into the besieged Moslem city
of Gorazde and its surroundings yesterday. In the town of Maglaj, civilians
huddled in basements and shelters as Serb gunners blasted Moslem targets.
In New York, the UN Security Council last night took a step towards
monitoring the Yugoslavia-Bosnia border, apparently including air
surveillance to check on weapons and other supplies to Bosnian Serbs. A
resolution, adopted by a 15-0 vote, asks the secretary-general to study
deployment and report back to the council, as well as seek intelligence on
border movements.
The measure is a far cry from earlier plans to deploy inspectors on the
Serb-dominated Yugoslav side of the Bosnian border, which diplomats last
month thought Belgrade would accept.
</TEXT>
