<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Lamont faces barrage of invective: Major refers to 'a little
local difficulty' as senior Tories hit back in his defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, ALISON SMITH and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN Lamont yesterday faced an unprecedented barrage of invective from
his erstwhile colleagues as Mr John Major's government struggled to regain
its balance in the wake of this week's onslaught by the former chancellor.
The attacks raised the possibility that the dangerous rift between the prime
minister and Mr Lamont might be prolonged. There were suggestions at
Westminster last night that intermediaries had told Mr Major's office that
the former chancellor was ready to respond in kind to any attempts to
discredit him.
In a further explosion of bitterness following Mr Lamont's dismissal two
weeks ago, Sir Norman Fowler, the Conservative party chairman, accused him
of 'thrashing around' in a 'nasty' and 'ludicrous' way to protect his own
reputation.
Others among his former cabinet colleagues said that Wednesday's assault on
the prime minister's leadership would be a 'nine-day wonder' as ministers
and senior backbench MPs launched a damage-limitation exercise to defend Mr
Major.
Mr Lamont was described as 'third-rate' by one minister who only two weeks
ago had sat with him around the cabinet table.
Conservative officials said a decision by the party last year to help the
then chancellor meet personal legal bills had created a backlash among Tory
supporters, costing it hundreds of thousands of pounds in potential
donations.
In the House of Commons, Mr Major made light of Mr Lamont's accusations that
his government acted as if it was 'in office but not in power'. Evoking the
phrase used by Mr Harold MacMillan when sacking Mr Peter Thorneycroft as
chancellor in 1958, Mr Major said the events represented a 'little local
difficulty'.
Brushing aside calls from Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, for an early
general election, Mr Major said he had no intention of commenting further on
Mr Lamont's statement.
But the prime minister will use a speech today to the Welsh Conservative
party to rebut Mr Lamont's claims that his government is preoccupied with
the short-term political effect of policy decisions. He intends to stress
his long-running commitment to keeping Britain at the centre of debate on
Europe's future and to beating inflation.
But the growing perception among its own supporters that the government is
consistently accident-prone was reinforced last night by the leak of
proposals by Mr Peter Lilley for large cuts in invalidity benefit.
Mr Major's more relaxed performance in the Commons was followed by a
carefully-crafted statement issued by the executive of the 1922 committee of
backbench Conservative MPs. The statement, agreed unanimously, offered the
prime minister '100 per cent support'.
Speaking after the weekly meeting of Conservative MPs, Sir Marcus Fox,
chairman of the committee, said that the statement had won a 'rapturous
reception' from the 150 or so backbenchers present.
Sir Marcus said all the contributions in the 15-minute meeting had supported
the prime minister, and had come from all shades of opinion within the
party. 'John Major is our prime minister, and will remain our prime minister
for a long time to come,' he said.
But the atmosphere of nervous calm did little to disguise concern among
ministers and backbench MPs that Mr Major's leadership remains in question.
Groups of rightwing MPs opposed to the Maastricht treaty were said to be
giving 'active consideration' to the possibility of a challenge to the prime
minister if the Conservatives lose the forthcoming Christchurch by-election.
Sir Marcus appeared to acknowledge the threat to Mr Major by calling for a
'change of style' by the government and suggesting that some of his advisers
might be replaced.
There were also the fears that Mr Lamont might react to any further attacks
by launching another assault on Mr Major, although he has told friends he
has no immediate plans to add to Mr Major's difficulties with a statement in
the near future or by enlarging on the themes in his speech on Wednesday.
He was relaxed about the impact of his comments, even though they had raised
questions about Mr Major's survival.
PM taunts Smith with election 'score', Page 6
Howard opposes independent bank move, Page 6
Tory infighting ends camaraderie, Page 7
Joe Rogaly, Page 12
Currencies, Page 25
London stocks, Page 34
</TEXT>
