<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 93 / Leaked plan to cut invalidity benefit attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT was last night threatened with another damaging political row
over its spending priorities after the leaking of plans to cut substantially
the cost of invalidity benefit.
A draft letter to the prime minister from Mr Peter Lilley, social security
secretary, sets out proposals to tax invalidity benefit, make it less
generous, focus it more on the long-term sick and introduce a tough medical
test to restrict its availability.
A clampdown on the benefit was widely expected but the leak's timing is
highly embarrassing for ministers as they struggle to restore calm in Tory
ranks after Mr Norman Lamont's damaging resignation speech.
The proposals, drawn up in agreement with Mr Michael Portillo, chief
secretary to the Treasury, would save Pounds 495m in the 1996-97 financial
year and Pounds 1.3bn a year by the end of the century.
But their impact on voters - particularly the elderly - will worry Tory MPs
already nervous about losing the forthcoming Christchurch by-election where
the Conservatives had a 23,000 majority in the general election. The letter
to the prime minister, apparently accidently leaked to the Press Association
news agency, says 'the changes are bound to be controversial' and reveals
that Mr Lilley failed last year to win cabinet approval for similar changes.
But it adds: 'I think the climate of opinion has now changed.' Mr Lilley
also says that Mr Portillo favoured still bigger cuts.
Mr Gordon Brown, Labour's Treasury spokesman, said Mr John Major had accused
Labour of scaremongering in the past but now 'has no credibility left and is
guilty of a gross deception on the British public'.
The number of invalidity benefit claimants has grown from 600,000 in 1978-79
to 1.5m today while the cost has soared from Pounds 840m to Pounds 6.2bn
over the same period - an increase that ministers do not believe corresponds
to a rise in invalidity cases.
Mr Lilley proposes restricting the changes to new benefit claimants. His
letter says: 'Taxation would introduce an element of means testing which
would be more acceptable than means testing the benefit itself.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
