<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Banks count the cost of their biggest mistake: Free banking
was widely welcomed. John Gapper charts its introduction - and the rush to
abolish it
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BRIAN Pearse, chief executive of the bank that introduced free banking
for customers in credit, is characteristically blunt about the wisdom of the
move. 'Free banking was one of the two biggest mistakes ever made by high
street banks,' he told a building society conference last week.
Mr Pearse was chief executive of Barclays' US operation when Midland made
its move in 1984, shortly followed by the others.
The second mistake, in his view, was that banks did not co-operate to form a
common cash machine network. The second mistake is likely to remain in place
longer than the first.
The problems created by not charging customers unless they go into overdraft
 -and then imposing disproportionate charges - are increasingly pressing.
All banks are now considering charges to offset the annual Pounds 4.5bn cost
of services such as the 30 withdrawals each customer makes from cash
machines.
Abbey's disclosure yesterday that it is likely to introduce charging for
customers in credit will accelerate plans. Mr Tim Melville Ross,
Nationwide's chief executive, emphasised this week that the building society
would follow with charges on its FlexAccount if the big banks started
charging.
The pace of competition has accelerated because falls in base rates have
reduced earnings from banks' interest-free deposits.
The reduced return on 'free resources' lost National Westminster Bank 0.57
percentage points of interest on its Pounds 67.3bn UK interest-bearing
assets last year - or Pounds 380m.
Mr Richard Goeltz, NatWest's chief financial officer, says the effect on
profits was far lower because NatWest has 'hedged' its assets to reduce the
overall effects of interest rate movements. But banks now think they could
not sustain 'free' banking if base rates fell to 5 per cent.
But charges are a sensitive matter. About 6,000 customers of Save &amp; Prosper,
the small retail bank run by Robert Fleming, were directly affected when it
introduced a monthly charge for customers whose current account balances
fell below Pounds 1,000 at the end of the month. It has since lost 5,000 of
them.
Banks also anticipate a huge re-shuffling of accounts with an uncertain
final outcome following the re-introduction of charges because 13 per cent
of customers now hold more than one account. They may be prompted to choose
between them by the prospect of paying charges on a little-used one.
The ideal effect of re-introducing charges for banks would be that they lose
customers who are not worth keeping. But this does not necessarily mean
losing all the customers whose current accounts do not support the annual
cost of between Pounds 35 and Pounds 75 for the provision of basic clearing
services.
Many such customers hold other products such as savings accounts which make
them profitable overall. But no UK bank yet has the technology to calculate
this figure, and apply charges accordingly.
Mr Ian Lindsey, Save &amp; Prosper's banking director, says it is at least three
years away.
An alternative approach would be to charge customers per transaction to
ensure that those who cost most pay most. The difficulty is that this is
clearly unpopular.
Abbey National's own research found that 88 per cent of people thought fees
for 'core' transactions such as statements were unfair.
This is likely to push banks towards imposing a flat-rate fee per quarter or
month if a customer's balance falls below a certain level. This is dubbed
the 'Disneyworld' charge - a single pass to all attractions - by Professor
David Llewellyn, banking professor at Loughborough University.
Prof Llewellyn argues, however, that a better approach would be a 'two tier'
structure adopted by utilities which have high fixed costs attached to
distribution networks, such as British Telecom. This means a fixed quarterly
fee, plus additional charges for heavy use of some discretionary services.
Prof Llewellyn, whose recent study of the subject has been read closely by
Abbey, also argues that consumers should be given a choice of charging
structures to soften the blow.
But Abbey's decision makes it likely that the choice will come sooner than
many bank customers might wish.
