<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / World Trade News: US to re-ignite row on aircraft subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE transatlantic trade dispute over commercial aircraft subsidies is set to
flare up again on the eve of the Paris Air Show, the world's biggest, with
growing signs that the US is seeking to lower the ceiling for direct
government subsidies for new airliner programmes from 33 per cent to 20 per
cent.
The Clinton administration appears increasingly intent in renegotiating the
bilateral agreement reached last year between the US and the European
Commission on aircraft subsidies which fixed the 33 per cent ceiling on
direct government subsidies for new aircraft programmes.
Senior officials of the European Airbus consortium yesterday claimed during
a Financial Times aerospace conference that the US was now trying to use a
clause in the 1992 agreement calling for multilateralisation of the
bilateral accord in which the subsidy ceiling would be reduced to 20 per
cent.
This is regarded by Airbus as a transparent attempt by the US to put into
question the original bilateral agreement, which took five years to
negotiate, while making no additional concessions on the level of indirect
funding that the US aerospace industry receives.
In the 1992 agreement, the amount of indirect subsidies were capped at 3 per
cent of the annual turnover of the country's aerospace industry.
Mr Wolfgang Piller, executive vice president of Deutsche Aerospace, one of
the four Airbus partners, told the conference that the Europeans were now
demanding 'complete transparency' from the US over its indirect support to
its aerospace companies.
'The Europeans have a real handicap in that they are unable, at the present
time, to match the indirect subsidies of the US, which, according to some
estimates, amount to about Dollars 1bn a year,' he said.
He described the Clinton Administration's stand on the aircraft subsidy
issue as 'hypocritical and unfair'. The US has consistently attacked
government subsidies for the Airbus programme as unfairly damaging US
commercial aerospace companies, especially at a time when the whole industry
was in recession. In recent years, Airbus has been aggressively increasing
its penetration of the US airliner market.
Other Airbus executives expressed concern over the latest US moves which
they feel are designed to undermine the European consortium's efforts to
develop a new very large aircraft, which would challenge Boeing's dominance
of the jumbo market.
The Airbus officials said the EC was expected to reject outright the latest
US proposals to multilateralise the bilateral aircraft subsidy agreement.
The original idea was to extend the agreement to cover other aerospace
manufacturing countries, notably Japan. But the Airbus executives said if
the US sought to use this process as a ploy to renegotiate the subsidy
ceilings in the bilateral agreement, the EC would simply oppose the
multilateralisation of the accord.
Rolls-Royce, the UK aero-engine manufacturer, also noted that the US had so
far refused to consider extending the aircraft subsidy agreement to cover
aero-engines. The UK group said this reflected the fact that its two big US
aero-engine rivals, General Electric and Pratt &amp; Whitney, received
significant more support from their government than Rolls-Royce.
</TEXT>
