<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Gasholder damaged after bomb explosion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANTI TERRORIST squad officers joined police forensic scientists and an Army
bomb disposal squad yesterday searching land near to a Gateshead gasholder
which was damaged early on Wednesday by an explosion and fire, Chris Tighe
writes.
More than 400 people were evacuated from nearby homes but nobody was injured
and there was no damage outside the site, the biggest gasholder compound in
Tyneside.
Detective chief superintendent Barry Stewart, head of Northumbria police
CID, said the incident was being treated as a crime.
It was too early to say how the explosion was caused. However, it resembled
an explosion in April at the Esso oil storage terminal in North Shields for
which the IRA claimed responsibility.
British Gas Northern chairman Mr James Marris said it was very unlikely that
the incident was caused by normal operations.
The company confirmed that the intruder alarm had sounded. An off-duty
British Gas employee living nearby raised the alarm and 80 firefighters
fought the blaze for an hour.
The gas supply to the gasholder was immediately cut off. The hole is now
under water. It will be weeks before it can be examined.
Earlier this year the IRA claimed responsibility for an explosion and fire
at a gasholder in Warrington, Cheshire.
</TEXT>
