<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Effortless cheer marks Clarke's
debut as chancellor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT LAST the Conservatives had someone to cheer.
Mr Kenneth Clarke's first appearance as chancellor at the Commons despatch
box offered nothing to anyone hoping for an insight into his thinking on the
intricacies of monetary or fiscal policy.
But then the sullen, serried ranks of Tory MPs who had earlier sat through
his predecessor's savage attack on the prime minister were not in the mood
for amateur economics.
Bemused and bewildered at their party's infallible ability to shoot itself
in the head, they wanted their spirits lifted: a politician to wipe the
beaming grins of their counterparts on the opposition benches.
Mr Clarke delivered. The man who had admitted earlier in the day that, yes,
he had been known to cross the street to start a fight, set about Mr Gordon
Brown.
The shadow chancellor was congratulated on his jokes. Mr Clarke admitted
that even he sometimes found it difficult not to laugh at the jibes directed
at his cabinet colleagues.
But where was Labour's policy? Mr Brown's speech had had 'about as much
policy content as the average telephone directory'. He warmed to the theme:
'The best parts of it came when you were quoting me.'
The Tory MPs who had sat glumly through Mr John Major's defence of his
record cheered. Mr Clarke raised the level of invective. An attempted
interruption by a Mr Peter Mandelson, Labour's one-time campaigns
co-ordinator and image-maker brought a scornful dismissal of his party's
reliance on public relations glitz.
'If you think we have achieved what we have achieved so far and what we are
going to achieve by plastic red roses and smart suits you have another think
coming'.
The Tories cheered again, louder. Mr Clarke stuck with the theme. There was
nothing original in attacking Labour for refusing to offer its alternatives.
Mr Lamont in his time had used the technique effectively.
But Mr Clarke - just 14 days in the most difficult job in the government -
exhibited effortlessly the political skills which his predecessor so sadly
lacked: confidence, humour, and above all, a willingness to discuss economic
policy in the terms understood by the voters. Mr Clarke's Treasury would
concern itself with the real world - with jobs, with business. The Tories
cheered again.
There was just time for a few thoughts on economic policy, Echoing earlier
media interviews, Mr Clarke spoke of his determination to sustain the
recovery, to hold down inflation, to tackle the 'iceberg' of the public
sector borrowing requirement. He reminded his backbench fans he would expect
their support when he took the hard decisions needed to restrain public
spending.
Mr Clarke sat down to a roar of approval. Mr Major patted him on the back.
As the two men walked towards the voting lobbies, their colleagues on the
backbenches kept their thoughts to themselves.
The government subsequently secured a majority of 24 (302-278) to defeat a
Labour motion condemning the prime minister's 'betrayal of election promises
and commitments on economic and social policy'.
A government amendment deploring 'scaremongering stories' about public
spending peddled by Labour MPs was carried by a majority of 30.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
