<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major dismisses monetary union
deadline - Sacked chancellor rounds on PM as politics overshadows economics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING WAS unlikely to return to the European exchange rate mechanism for
some years - perhaps not before the election - Mr John Major said yesterday
as he made clear his belief that the idea of monetary union in 1997 was
'wholly unrealistic'.
Prompted by the statement from Mr Norman Lamont, the prime minister
expressed some sympathy for the possibility of an independent central bank.
During Mr Major's speech itself, which was marked throughout by rowdy
interventions from opposition MPs, politics overshadowed econ-omics in the
Commons chamber.
One Tory backbencher intervened, however, to praise the prime minister for
emphasising that for the UK to rejoin the ERM there would have to be greater
convergence of the monetary policies of all the main European Community
economies, and the mechanism would have to operate to the benefit of all its
members.
'I now doubt whether these circumstances will apply for some years ahead -
possibly not in this parliament,' Mr Major said.
But he insisted that his view that the EC countries would not be ready for a
single currency for many years, if ever, was not 'anti-European'. Instead it
came from his belief that the conditions would not then be in place and that
the damage from a premature move towards monetary union would be profound.
While agreeing that there was a case for giving independence to the Bank of
England, Mr Major said that the underlying policy was more important than
the institutional arrangements. He did not believe, he said, that an
independent central bank would have brought inflation down more quickly than
the government had achieved.
His main concern was that politicians should still be able to call to
account those who made decisions about monetary policy.
'Were a way to be found to get the benefits of an independent central bank
without a loss of parliamentary accountability, my views would be closer to
yours,' Mr Major told his former chancellor.
His tribute to Mr Lamont, that 'history will look favourably on your
economic and financial skills', provoked Labour jeers of 'Why did you sack
him then?'.
That question was effectively answered as Mr Major continued: 'But a strong
government needs political skills as well when leading a democratic society
and, in particular, handling a lively House of Commons with a small
majority.'
The political impact of the government's likely public spending decisions on
Tory backbenchers already worried about the possibilities being floated, was
clearly in Mr Major's mind as he set out the basis of the spending review.
The criteria would be, he said, whether any changes were fair and whether
vulnerable people were protected. 'I did not come into politics to dismantle
the welfare state.'
But he sought also to dismiss the accusation by Mr Lamont that ministers
were more concerned to take popular than right decisions. He said that in
tackling the state of the public finances the government was taking
long-term views, not going for short-term options.
This was in stark contrast to the attitude of the other parties, he said,
attacking Labour for 'contracting out' the difficult decisions to be taken
on welfare benefits to its commission on social justice.
The prime minister also mounted a vehement attack on Mr John Smith, as he
contrasted the Labour leader's reputation for honour with the
'scare-mongering' tactics of his party. 'In the Labour party the scares come
from the top - behind that moral righteousness is someone who has no
scruples whatsoever,' Mr Major said.
When he sat down at the end of his speech it was MPs on the opposition
benches who shouted for more.
</TEXT>
<XX>
